This is a master issue of issues/improvements needed for NGCC async mode to be more successful with the CLI integration.

1) Allow termination (CTRL+C) - Currently it is not possible to terminate NGCC async process. 
2) Clustering issue - Fork clustering without properly setting up the master is not ideal when used via the API. More context in: TOOL-1339 (Can be solved by using `cluster.setupMaster`)
3) Unable to provide a custom logger. As a workaround and interim for the issue 2. In the CLI we will most likely setup the cluster master ourselves in the webpack plugin. However with this approach we cannot use a custom logger

```ts
cluster.setupMaster({
  exec: require.resolve('@angular/compiler-cli/ngcc/main-ngcc.js'),
  args: [
    '--basePath',
    this._nodeModulesDirectory,
    '--propertiesToConsider',
    ...this.propertiesToConsider,
    '--compileAllFormats',
    'false',
    '--async',
  ],
});
```
3) Reduce worker code path - Reduce workers by pointing the cluster workers to start from a different entrypoint (Can use `cluster.setupMaster()`), this should speed up the worker boot time.
4) Don't spawn unneeded workers - Spawning workers is expensive and currently we are spawning unwanted workers, when 1, there are no packages to process, 2, when we need to process a number of packages which is less than the available CPU count - 1. 
5) Running the new integration NGCC async as opposed to NGCC sync during module resolution causes a build time regression of 8/10 seconds on an `ng new` application with Angular Material when all modules have been processed previously. (Seems to be related to `analyzeEntryPoints`) Note: in my app I am importing all material entrypoints. 
